Station Narrative: Above Bates River, Pacific-Yukon Region YT08AB0009, Water Quality Monitoring Branch - Environment Canada, November 2004. Site is located in Kluane National Park, 180 km WSW of Whitehorse, 75 km SSW of Haines Junction, 2.9 km upstream of Bates River and 13 km north of the BC Border. WSC station 08AB001.
Responsible Collection Agency: Environment Canada - Water Science and Technology Branch

Station Narrative: At Upper Crosing on Alaska Highway, Pacific-Yukon Region YT10AA0001, Water Quality Monitoring Branch - Environment Canada, November 2004. The Liard River is a major tributary of the Mackenzie River, flowing southeast from the Yukon into British Columbia, looping through northern B.C., and then flowing northeast into the Northwest Territories to the Mackenzie. Water quality is affected by mining and forestry. This report assesses water quality data collected at the Upper Crossing monitoring station located at the Alaska Highway bridge near the Yukon-B.C. border. Water quality samples were collected between 1983 and 1994 by Environment Canada. Flow was measured at a Water Survey of Canada flow gauge at the water quality monitoring station. We concluded that there were no environmentally significant trends in water quality that could be identified through visual examination of the data. Total aluminum, cadmium, iron, manganese and zinc at times exceeded water quality criteria for drinking water or aquatic life due to high levels of suspended sediment during high river flow. These metals were probably not bio-available and would be removed by drinking water treatment needed to remove turbidity. The river had a low sensitivity to acid inputs. We recommend that monitoring be terminated for the Liard River at Upper Crossing because there are no apparent water quality trends or concerns at this time.  Site is located in the town of Upper Liard, approximately 11 km west of Watson Lake, YT. Sampled from downstream side of the Alaska Hwy bridge during open water (walkway only on downstream side) and accessed from left bank upstream of bridge during the winter. Water Survey Station 10AA001.
Responsible Collection Agency: Environment Canada - Water Science and Technology Branch

Station Narrative: Above Old Crow, Pacific-Yukon Region YT09FB0003, Water Quality Monitoring Branch - Environment Canada, November 2004. Porcupine River above Old Crow River was turbid during higher flows and open water, exceeding the recreation guideline during spring freshet, and exceeding drinking water guidelines during open water, necessitating turbidity removal before drinking water use. The turbidity caused several metals to exceed water quality guidelines due to the metal content of the turbidity. Colour and dissolved organic carbon often exceeded drinking water guidelines, and an investigation would be needed if the water was chlorinated before use. Water temperature exceeded the aesthetic drinking water guideline in summer, and the maximum guideline for fish was exceeded in two summers. During winter, hardness exceeded the poor, but tolerable, guideline for drinking water. Site is located approximately 600m upstream of the confluence with Old Crow River, 3 km upstream of the town of Old Crow, YT and 90 km upstream of the Alaska Border. Water Survey Station 09FD003.
Responsible Collection Agency: Environment Canada - Water Science and Technology Branch

Station Narrative: At Park Entrance, Pacific-Yukon Region BC08ND0003, Water Quality Monitoring Branch - Environment Canada, November 2004. The watershed above the Illecillewaet River water quality station has a drainage area of 203 km2 in the Purcell Mountains and lies completely within Glacier National Park. The watershed is relatively pristine, with high recreational values. The only potential anthropogenic influences on water quality of the Beaver River are the Trans-Canada highway and Canadian National Railway mainline which both run through the park, recreational activities in the park, and deposition of airborne contaminants. No water quality concerns or significant trends have been noted at the site to date. Site located upstream of Highway 1 and railroad bridge in Glacier National Park. River crosses Hwy 1 twice in the park, access site at eastern Hwy crossing. Small trail down to river can be accessed via small parking lot. Sampled from right bank.
Responsible Collection Agency: Environment Canada - Water Science and Technology Branch

Station Narrative: Above Field, Pacific-Yukon Region BC08NA0033, Water Quality Monitoring Branch - Environment Canada, November 2004. The Kicking Horse River above Field, B.C. drains 244 km2 of the Rocky Mountains in the headwaters of the Columbia River basin. This is a relatively pristine watershed, lying completely within Yoho National Park, and it has high recreational values. The river has been designated as a Heritage River by the Canadian Heritage Rivers Board due to its outstanding natural and historical features. The main potential anthropogenic influences on water quality come from the Trans-Canada Highway, the CN Railway mainline, recreational activities in the park, and atmospheric deposition. The Kicking Horse River above Field, B.C. is one of 4 National Parks sites included in the Federal Water Quality Monitoring Network in British Columbia. Other stations are located on the Beaver and Illecillewaet Rivers in Mount Revelstoke/Glacier National Parks, and the Kootenay River in Kootenay National Park. Sampled from right bank, access from Yoho National Park Visitor Centre in Field, BC.
Responsible Collection Agency: Environment Canada - Water Science and Technology Branch

Station Narrative: At Waneta, Pacific-Yukon Region BC08NE0001, Water Quality Monitoring Branch - Environment Canada, November 2004. Site located 3 km upstream of confluence with Pend d'Oreille River. Site accessed off of Hwy 22A (Waneta Hwy), south of Montrose, via large pull off and trail to river. Sampled from left bank. The water quality site on the Columbia River at Waneta is 25 km downstream from the Birchbank water quality site, and 16 km south of the community of Trail. Water quality in this reach of the Columbia River is influenced by effluent discharges from the Cominco Metals Smelter and Fertilizer plant, primary-treated sewage from the City of Trail, and secondary-treated sewage from Fruitvale and Montrose. Improving trends in water quality over time at the Columbia River at Waneta due to effluent abatement at the Cominco Smelter and Fertilizer plant have been noted for: cadmium, chromium, fluoride, iron, lead, phosphorus, sulphate and zinc. The water quality objectives have been met in recent years for arsenic, lead, ammonia, pH, fecal coliforms and thallium, but were not met in 1995 or 1996 for cadmium, chromium, copper and zinc. The river has a low sensitivity to acid inputs. Columbia River water at Waneta must be treated to remove turbidity and disinfected prior to drinking. The maximum water temperature guidelines for salmonids have been met on all but one of the sampling occasions. More station details available at: http://aquatic.pyr.ec.gc.ca/webdataonlinenational/en/SiteDetails/BC08NE0001/Projects/PYLTM/Regions/0
Responsible Collection Agency: Environment Canada - Water Science and Technology Branch

Station Narrative: At Daisy Lake Forest Road, Pacific-Yukon Region BC08GA0010, Water Quality Monitoring Branch - Environment Canada, November 2004. Sampled from left bank approximately 200m upstream of Daisy Lake Forest Road bridge.
Responsible Collection Agency: Environment Canada - Water Science and Technology Branch

Station Narrative: At Highway 93 near Elko, Pacific-Yukon Region BC08NK0003, Water Quality Monitoring Branch - Environment Canada, November 2004. The Elk River watershed is located in the southeast corner of British Columbia. The water quality sampling site is located near the confluence of the Elk River and Lake Koocanusa (on the Kootenay River). This report is based on 11 years of Environment Canada data and a decade of provincial data. One of the main human activities influencing the water quality in the Elk River Valley is open pit coal mining. The amount of coal mining has nearly doubled over the last decade. Selenium levels increased over the decade and the Elk River had among the highest selenium concentrations of any federal-provincial monitoring station in B.C. This appears to have been caused by the disturbance of selenium-bearing soils during coal mining. Peak arsenic concentrations increased, but were still below water quality criteria. Nitrate/nitrite and total dissolved nitrogen concentrations increased over the decade. Water hardness reached a level where water quality was poor for domestic use during the winter, and may have been increasing. We recommended continued monitoring at this station since there are several indicators that exceeded criteria on a regular basis and/or were showing increasing trends. Continued investigations are also recommended to determine the sources of the selenium and arsenic and their potential environmental effects. The results of these investigations will help to show the type of corrective action, if any, which may be needed to reduce selenium or arsenic levels. Sampled from left bank upstream of Highway 93 bridge, approximately 14 km SW. of Elko. More station details available at: http://aquatic.pyr.ec.gc.ca/webdataonlinenational/en/SiteDetails/BC08NK0003/Projects/PYLTM/Regions/0
Responsible Collection Agency: Environment Canada - Water Science and Technology Branch

Station Narrative: At Red Pass, Pacific-Yukon Region BC08KA0007, Water Quality Monitoring Branch - Environment Canada, November 2004. The water quality monitoring site at Red Pass is the first of five long-term monitoring stations on the Fraser River. This site represents a relatively pristine monitoring station, with no significant anthropogenic activity occurring upstream from this location. There has been an increasing trend in nickel concentrations since about 1994. The cause of this increase is unclear, but concentrations of total nickel remain well below guideline levels for aquatic life. Specific conductivity also appears to be increasing over time, but the levels are well below water quality guidelines. The Fraser River at Red Pass has a low sensitivity to acid inputs (has a high buffering capacity) based on its relatively high total alkalinity and calcium concentrations. Exceedances of water quality guidelines by metals such as total aluminum, total iron, and total silver, appear to be associated with elevated turbidity levels, indicating that these metals are bound in particulate matter, and therefore not available to biota and not of concern. As there are no anthropogenic activities upstream from the Red Pass site, the measured concentrations of all metals would appear to be due to natural erosion processes in the upper watershed. Occasional high turbidity values are also attributed to natural erosion processes. Fecal coliform values have been very low. True colour has only been measured at Red Pass since 1997, but all values since that time have been below the aesthetic guideline for drinking water quality. Red Pass Junction, near outlet of Moose Lake. Sampled from right bank downstream of CN bridge. WSC Station 08KA007.
Responsible Collection Agency: Environment Canada - Water Science and Technology Branch

Station Narrative: At Oliver, Pacific-Yukon Region BC08NM0001, Water Quality Monitoring Branch - Environment Canada, November 2004. The Okanagan River at Oliver is located in the southern interior region of BC, just upstream from Osoyoos Lake. The river originates at the south end of Okanagan Lake near Penticton and flows south through Skaha, Vaseux, and Osoyoos lakes. Osoyoos Lake straddles the border with the United States. Urbanisation, agriculture and logging are the major human impacts in the south Okanagan. The sampling site is between Oliver and Osoyoos Lake. Water quality data have been collected by Environment Canada for 15 years and by the province for ten years. No environmentally significant trends in water quality were detected by visual assessment of the data. Fecal coliforms may have exceeded the criterion for raw drinking water receiving disinfection only. Turbidity removal and disinfection are recommended prior to drinking. Water temperatures were quite high -  good in the spring and summer for recreation, but not for fisheries or drinking water supplies. We recommend continued monitoring of water quality and flow for the Okanagan River at Oliver because of its proximity to Osoyoos Lake, a transboundary water body. Sampled from upstream side of the Road 18 bridge, approx. 8 km south of Oliver, B.C.
Responsible Collection Agency: Environment Canada - Water Science and Technology Branch

Station Narrative: At Highway 1 Bridge, Pacific-Yukon Region BC08LE0004, Water Quality Monitoring Branch - Environment Canada, November 2004. The Salmon River is typical of interior B.C. streams, with flows dominated by a snow-melt freshet in May and June. Turbidity values are frequently above guideline levels. Exceedences of water quality guidelines by metals such as aluminum, cadmium, cobalt, copper, iron, and manganese are likely a result of occasional high concentrations of particulate matter (as evidenced by the high turbidity levels). This means that these metals are probably not bioavailable and would be removed by the treatment needed before use as drinking water. The Salmon River has a low sensitivity to acid inputs (is well-buffered), as evidenced by high alkalinity and calcium concentrations. Both of these parameters show strong seasonal fluctuations associated with water level. Fecal coliform concentrations have generally been much higher than the guideline for drinking water undergoing disinfection only. Dissolved organic carbon and true colour values frequently exceed the drinking water guideline at this site. Fluoride concentrations occasionally exceed the aquatic life guidelines. Salmon River water has relatively high hardness, frequently exceeding the optimum aesthetic range for drinking water. Phosphorus concentrations are relatively high at this site, and may be contributing to eutrophication in Shuswap Lake. At old Highway 1 bridge near Salmon Arm. Sampled from upstream side of bridge.
Responsible Collection Agency: Environment Canada - Water Science and Technology Branch

Station Narrative: At the Border, Pacific-Yukon Region BC08NL0005, Water Quality Monitoring Branch - Environment Canada, November 2004. Similkameen River water is used for irrigation, livestock watering, drinking, primary and secondary-contact recreation, and industrial use, and it sustains aquatic life and wildlife. Exceedences of water quality guidelines by metals such as aluminum, arsenic, cadmium, cobalt, copper, iron, manganese, and zinc are likely a result of occasional high concentrations of particulate matter (as evidenced by high turbidity levels). This means that these metals are probably not bioavailable and would be removed by the treatment needed before use as drinking water. The Similkameen River has a low sensitivity to acid inputs (is relatively well-buffered), as evidenced by relatively high calcium concentrations. True colour values have frequently exceeded the drinking water guideline at this site. Weak-acid dissociable cyanide concentrations have exceeded the average aquatic life guideline on only one occasion, and have not exceeded the maximum guideline. Strong-acid dissociable cyanide concentrations are well below guideline levels. Fluoride concentrations occasionally exceed the aquatic life guidelines. The Similkameen River has moderate hardness, with concentrations generally within the optimum drinking water range. Water temperatures exceed the aesthetic drinking water guideline and the general fisheries guideline most years. Turbidity values are frequently above guideline levels for drinking water (both aesthetic and health). Site is located approximately 9 km north of the U.S. Border at the Chopaka Road bridge crossing, exit off of Highway 3A. Sampled from upstream side of bridge.
Responsible Collection Agency: Environment Canada - Water Science and Technology Branch

Station Narrative: At Kilbridge, Newfoundland, NF02ZM0009, Water Quality Monitoring Branch - Environment Canada, November 2004. Waterford River at Kilbride. This is a real-time station. This is a chemical monitoring station. Access this site by traveling south on Columbus Drive, straight through the intersection of Columbus Drive and Topsail Road, and take a left at the intersection of Columbus Drive and Bay Bulls Road. Take an immediate left from Bay Bulls Road onto Mackey Place and park in the commercial parking lot adjacent to the Bowering Park walking trail. Follow the walking trail into Bowring Park for about 50 feet, until you come to a grassy field with an overgrown driveway marked by two wooden posts. Follow the  driveway to the embankment at the river's edge. Collect samples directly behind the real time water quality shelter.  Waterford River originates at Bremigans Pond in Paradise.  It flows southeast to Bowring Park along Topsail Road.  Before arriving in Bowring Park many rivers and ponds flow into it such as Nevilles Pond, Powers Pond, and Flings Brook.  As well, many unnamed tributaries flow into it.  In Bowring Park, South Brook joins Waterford River before leaving the Park and flowing directly alongside Waterford Bridge Road to the Harbour.  Before it reaches the St. John's Harbour, however, Beaver Pond and Mundy Pond both drain into the river. The distance from the headwaters to the sampling site (NF02ZM0009) is 12.9 km and the distance from the sampling site to the mouth is 3.7 km. Downstream of the sampling site there is one sampling site at Blackhead Road (NF02ZM0181) and there are 3 others upstream, at Bremigans Pond (NF02ZM0182), Commonwealth Avenue (NF02ZM0004), and Brookfield Road (NF02ZM0175).
Responsible Collection Agency: Environment Canada - Water Science and Technology Branch

Station Narrative: Newfoundland, NF03QC0001, Water Quality Monitoring Branch - Environment Canada, November 2004. This is a chemical monitoring station.  This is a core CESI station. The site is only accessible by helicopter.  Station located on the left bank of Eagle River above Big Falls West of Cartwright.  Sampling is conducted on the north bank near the gauging station.  Channel is wide at station with an island approximately 500m below.  Right bank is steep and heavily treed and left bank sand and relatively flat.    The sampling site is located approximately 14 km from the Eagle River outlet into Sandwich Bay. This upland plateau is composed of extensive string bogs with numerous open pools surrounded by fen vegetation. Bog hummocks are dominated by scrub spruce, Labrador tea, and feathermoss. The peatland expanses are occasionally interrupted by only a few conspicuous eskers, which support open, lichen woodland. Alder thickets are common along river banks.
Responsible Collection Agency: Environment Canada - Water Science and Technology Branch
